      "<b>Part 2: The Legislature</b>:<br><br>Description:<br>The legislature is the organ of government responsible for making laws. It consists of elected representatives who debate and vote on proposed laws.<br><br>Key Functions of the Legislature:<br>1. Law Making:<br>The primary function is to create, amend, or repeal laws that govern the country.<br><br>2. Representation:<br>Legislators represent the interests and views of the citizens in their constituencies.<br><br>3. Budget Approval:<br>The legislature reviews and approves the government’s budget, influencing how public money is spent.<br><br>Activity:<br>Have students role-play a simple legislative session where they propose a new rule for the classroom, discuss it, and vote on it.",
      "<b>Part 3: The Executive</b>:<br><br>Description:<br>The executive is the organ of government responsible for implementing and enforcing laws. It is headed by the president or prime minister and includes various ministers and government officials.<br><br>Key Functions of the Executive:<br>1. Law Enforcement:<br>The executive ensures that laws passed by the legislature are carried out and enforced.<br><br>2. Policy Making:<br>The executive develops policies that guide how laws will be implemented and how government services will be delivered.<br><br>3. Public Administration:<br>The executive oversees the administration of public services and government operations.<br><br>Discussion:<br>Discuss with students who they think is in charge of enforcing rules in their school and how those rules are applied.",
